1
00:00:00,706 --> 00:00:17,500
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudassa

2
00:00:18,053 --> 00:00:27,385
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa.

3
00:00:27,405 --> 00:00:31,870
Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed Noble and the Fully Self-Enlightened One.

4
00:00:36,237 --> 00:00:41,984
So these Sanyojana, these fetters, remember there were ten of them, I'll just run through them quickly again.

5
00:00:42,353 --> 00:00:49,094
The idea of self, the personality belief, this personality being me.

6
00:00:50,258 --> 00:00:53,749
Skeptical doubt, doubt in the Buddha's teaching.

7
00:00:53,768 --> 00:00:56,076
This is specific to doubt in the Buddha's teaching.

8
00:00:56,865 --> 00:01:15,647
Clinging to mere rules and rituals, that means thinking that rules and rituals are material, directly material to the process of liberation, as some practice in the East, believing, for instance, that standing in the Ganges gets rid of your karma, stuff like that.

9
00:01:17,168 --> 00:01:20,352
The fourth and fifth are sensual craving and ill will.

10
00:01:21,013 --> 00:01:26,838
And then the sixth and seventh are these rupa jhanas, based on...

11
00:01:26,819 --> 00:01:34,192
Rūpaṇa, Rūpa-jāna, the absorptions, you know, based on Samatha meditation.

12
00:01:35,134 --> 00:01:38,680
Then there's restlessness and finally ignorance.

13
00:01:38,700 --> 00:01:47,798
So the Sotapanna, the stream entrance, someone who's glimpsed Nibbāna, the Buddha talks about it like a flash of lightning.

14
00:01:48,149 --> 00:01:52,575
has got rid of the first three.

15
00:01:53,216 --> 00:01:55,579
Now there's another lovely image that the Buddha gives us.

16
00:01:55,620 --> 00:02:02,650
So we had the image of the Sotapanna, like a flash of lightning sees everything, but it is only a flash.

17
00:02:03,611 --> 00:02:15,169
And the once-returner, the Anagami, the Sakadagami, he or she, of course, is like a full starlit night.

18
00:02:15,992 --> 00:02:24,985
The non-returner, the anagama, is like a full moon night and the arahat sees things clearly as the sun at midday.

19
00:02:25,646 --> 00:02:26,487
That's the image he gives.

20
00:02:26,508 --> 00:02:30,813
But there's another rather interesting image which tells us about the effort.

21
00:02:32,034 --> 00:02:40,987
Ordinary people are swimming under the water, he says, and the stream entrant is one whose head keeps bobbing up out of the water.

22
00:02:41,861 --> 00:02:46,747
The once-returner is the person who can tread water.

23
00:02:47,028 --> 00:02:48,691
So the head's always above water, you see.

24
00:02:49,611 --> 00:02:58,263
And the person who is swimming towards once-returner is actually making the effort to get to the island.

25
00:02:58,282 --> 00:02:58,864
It's a swim.

26
00:03:00,104 --> 00:03:03,229
And the adahat is somebody who's landed on the island.

27
00:03:04,407 --> 00:03:07,151
So it gives you two points of real effort.

28
00:03:07,251 --> 00:03:14,699
The first one is coming out of that fundamental delusion into the first glimpse of Nibbāna.

29
00:03:15,622 --> 00:03:18,586
And the second one, the difficult one, is getting to a non-returner.

30
00:03:18,945 --> 00:03:22,030
And the reason for that is that you're leaving the sensual world.

31
00:03:22,531 --> 00:03:27,377
So the once-returner

32
00:03:27,356 --> 00:03:34,925
It's somebody who has attenuated their sensual desire and ill will.

33
00:03:35,485 --> 00:03:41,991
But it doesn't go at all, their aversion doesn't go at all until they get to the state of non-returner.

34
00:03:42,853 --> 00:03:48,799
And what that means is that that being no longer desires to come back to this realm of existence.

35
00:03:48,818 --> 00:03:50,020
There's nothing attracting them here.

36
00:03:50,420 --> 00:03:51,201
That's basically it.

37
00:03:51,222 --> 00:03:54,444
And that's why they're called non-returners.

38
00:03:54,997 --> 00:04:06,239
Now, there's still an attachment, and the attachment is to what the mind itself can produce, which are these beautiful states that we call the jhanas, the absorptions.

39
00:04:07,461 --> 00:04:12,449
And they have to get over that sort of attachment to going up there.

40
00:04:13,983 --> 00:04:24,221
People who practice that, of course, the more you practice that, the more you tend to want to be there because, in a sense, you're in control of that.

41
00:04:24,380 --> 00:04:31,574
Once you become an adept at jhana practice, you can enter it almost at will.

42
00:04:32,375 --> 00:04:36,041
So obviously, it's like having ice cream whenever you want it.

43
00:04:36,730 --> 00:04:41,357
There's no reason to come down for real ice cream when you can get it as a mental state.

44
00:04:42,098 --> 00:04:46,466
So that's one of the big problems of somebody who's an anagami.

45
00:04:46,485 --> 00:04:51,213
They're already very easily accessible, blissful states.

46
00:04:53,697 --> 00:05:00,166
And the last two things, sorry, the last three things.

47
00:05:00,187 --> 00:05:02,110
I don't think I mentioned conceit in that number 10.

48
00:05:02,129 --> 00:05:03,091
I must have missed it out.

49
00:05:04,252 --> 00:05:05,134
Yes, I missed it out.

50
00:05:05,194 --> 00:05:06,795
Conceit, restlessness and ignorance.

51
00:05:06,815 --> 00:05:07,675
They're the last three.

52
00:05:08,076 --> 00:05:10,899
Now, conceit, of course, is the self.

53
00:05:12,180 --> 00:05:16,024
And remember, conceit is always that comparison.

54
00:05:16,165 --> 00:05:23,072
The self is always comparing itself to somebody else or to another way of living.

55
00:05:23,252 --> 00:05:31,880
So it's always, I'm better than, or I'm worse than, I'm not as good as, or the more subtle one, I'm equal to.

56
00:05:32,079 --> 00:05:59,437
and when you say I'm equal to somebody you're basically creating a group and the group is not as good as or worse than something else so even though it might come out as a sort of humility well I'm equal to you actually it's just another form of conceit so I can't remember who said it but all comparison is odious and in a sense that's what the self does it's always comparing itself to others

57
00:05:59,822 --> 00:06:03,627
And that conceit only goes with the ending of self.

58
00:06:04,427 --> 00:06:09,992
So that's basically someone who has achieved the full enlightenment, the full awakening.

59
00:06:11,254 --> 00:06:28,411
Restlessness, I think here, the way I see it anyway, is that it's basically a lot of the old habits that a person has, but they're now so attenuated, they're now so small, that they're only felt as a sort of restlessness.

60
00:06:29,776 --> 00:06:33,288
So there's nothing particularly grave about such a person.

61
00:06:33,309 --> 00:06:38,487
By the time they get to an anagami, really they're very, very refined.

62
00:06:38,550 --> 00:06:44,579
The heart has been cleared of all its major obstacles because that's what keeps us here.

63
00:06:44,598 --> 00:06:50,127
So this sense of restlessness, I would presume, is very fine.

64
00:06:50,728 --> 00:06:53,971
And I'm thinking of people like the Mahasi Sayadaw whom I met.

65
00:06:56,055 --> 00:07:03,444
Some say that he was fully awakened and others say that he only attained this non-returner.

66
00:07:04,353 --> 00:07:07,576
At least that's what I got from the monks, so I don't know which is true.

67
00:07:07,617 --> 00:07:19,593
But the point, the thing about such a person is that you do feel that they have some extra virtue about them.

68
00:07:20,273 --> 00:07:23,697
In the case of the Mahasi, the feeling of silence.

69
00:07:23,718 --> 00:07:26,081
And it affects you as soon as you walk into the present.

70
00:07:26,100 --> 00:07:29,524
Your own head goes, your thoughts actually begin to stop.

71
00:07:29,545 --> 00:07:30,867
It has that sort of effect on you.

72
00:07:33,040 --> 00:07:39,045
So we're talking about somebody who has really refined their heart and clarified their understanding.

73
00:07:39,826 --> 00:07:47,074
And that's basically, you know, somebody who's moving towards being fully awakened.

74
00:07:47,875 --> 00:07:52,319
So really that takes us to the end of these sannyogina, these fetters.

75
00:07:53,781 --> 00:08:01,629
And I suppose the thing to say about them is that these are not under our control at all.

76
00:08:02,014 --> 00:08:03,538
They arise when the time is right.

77
00:08:04,519 --> 00:08:22,437
All we can do is practice to continuously purify the heart, to try and get rid of as many of these defilements as we can, or to work on them constantly, and through the vipassana to create that situation where insight can arise.

78
00:08:23,512 --> 00:08:32,611
But we don't have any direct, you know, we can't make this thing happen because this whole process is beyond the self.

79
00:08:33,097 --> 00:08:40,908
And that's one of these conundrums, one of these paradoxes, that you have to try, but you can't try and get something.

80
00:08:41,649 --> 00:08:46,657
So Zen puts it in that paradoxical way of the effortless effort.

81
00:08:47,157 --> 00:08:59,193
So as soon as your effort in meditation is to try and attain one of these piles of fruits, you're just creating an effort which is just knocking on the wrong door.

82
00:09:00,355 --> 00:09:01,317
It just ain't going to open.

83
00:09:03,101 --> 00:09:06,870
because these things cannot be attained by an act of will coming from the Self.

84
00:09:07,952 --> 00:09:14,768
And it's only when you drop that completely that insights arise, these vipassana insights arise.

85
00:09:16,672 --> 00:09:22,865
So that's why the Buddha's always insistent that we place the attention on

86
00:09:22,913 --> 00:09:31,133
the qualities of impermanence, of seeing how we're creating suffering for ourselves, and of seeing how we don't have control.

87
00:09:31,413 --> 00:09:33,557
That's the anatta doctrine, the not-self doctrine.

88
00:09:34,600 --> 00:09:40,956
And it's looking at, as things arise, as things arise in this present moment,

89
00:09:40,936 --> 00:09:56,190
from one of those three vantage points, that begins to liberate this pāññā, this wisdom that we have within us, this active, intuitive intelligence, intuitive awareness.

90
00:09:56,210 --> 00:09:57,892
And that's what does the job, you see.

91
00:09:57,912 --> 00:09:58,952
That's what does the job.

92
00:09:58,972 --> 00:10:00,114
That's where the insights come.

93
00:10:02,096 --> 00:10:08,461
So, what the Buddha here has done by giving us these fetters, is he shows us how

94
00:10:08,543 --> 00:10:23,958
Our delusion about the self, about how our defilements are all linked into the path, so that you can't have a growth of wisdom without the growth of virtue.

95
00:10:25,640 --> 00:10:27,261
They run parallel to each other.

96
00:10:29,323 --> 00:10:32,947
And that's basically what the Sanyojana are pointing to.

97
00:10:38,698 --> 00:10:42,216
So I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

98
00:10:42,235 --> 00:10:53,451
May you be liberated from all the fetters sooner rather than later.

